Trio Bistro has been serving the restaurant patrons of Washington DC since 1950. Anchored in the heart of Dupont Circle, Trio Bistro boasts two fully covered patios with outdoor seating and the main bar and dining area inside. With a beautiful view of Q Street and 17th Street, and surrounded by some of DC’s most desirable dining destinations, Trio Bistro naturally calls the heart of the city home. Whether you are looking to enjoy a casual night out after work with delicious food and unbeatable drink specials, or are planning a special event for larger groups, Trio Bistro can accommodate your occasion. We also offer bottomless champagne brunch every Saturday and Sunday! Don’t take our word for it though, come experience for yourself just why we have managed to stay in business for over 60 years … Bon Appetit!

This review isn't about the food. Because after 40 minutes of waiting we were barely given an opportunity to order food. It's about the terrible and unfriendly service. After being seated at our table, we waited for 20 minutes before the server came over. We ordered water and drinks and asked if the veggie burger was vegan. 10 minutes later, we had to grab her attention while cleaning the table next to us, and she said she still didn't no about the Veggie burger (still no water or drinks either). She was at a nearby table a few minutes later, and we called to her and asked again. She told us the burger was vegan but the bun was not. Then she literally turned her back to us and walked off without even asking us if we wanted to order it or anything else. We were really put off and decided that if our water and drinks didn't arrive within 5 min that we would leave. We ended up leaving and we're glad not to give them any money.  Now I know it is Pride, and all the businesses are slammed. But all we needed was to be acknowledged and treated respectfully, and told there would be a delay. But to be blatantly ignored and rudely spoken to is unacceptable. It also put us in a bad mood during a day that should be about celebrating ourselves. I live in the neighborhood and won't be returning to Trio again.

Waitress was wonderful. Pleasant. And efficient. And clear. Great personality. Cute and clean. I paid the minimum cash tip but it wasn't because she wasn't worth more. (Hence the review.) I think the owner was even across the room from us, just casually running thangs.  Food was REALLY good yo..big strong, lightly breaded and perfectly seasoned calamari; also had a chicken bruchette that was good as $#¡@. That came with 4 good mini sized pieces of grilled chicken (succulent, flavorful), tzatziki (Agora has some solid competition on the block!), and a lightly dressed up veg blend of onions, cucumbers, tomatoes...yeah, great food at good prices. Their menu selection theme  seems to be intended for under 18 yr olds, seinors, date night (small open bar area in front), quick bite, small plates, and libation. Oh! The drinks.  I had 2 mojitos. The first one was like lemonade. Or so I thought, as it hit me about 10 minutes later. The 2nd was good too, nice buzzy feeling. Light, perfectly blended drinks. I had instructions and the bartender followed them flawlessly.  Would definitely go again, mad I never stopped in at least for a drink before.  Lastly...no tvs. Good afternoon music, but owners might want to think about installing some as an investment.

This place is HORRIBLE.  Spent 25+ minutes waiting at the bar to order a drink. I watched and waited patiently as people around me were served continually getting passed over. After the man next to me commented on my lack of service I started to get frustrated. One of the three bar tenders made eye contact with me and then turned around completely ignoring me. The man next to me again commented on how that was such a tease. I laughed it off but then when I saw the same bar tender chilling and texting I decided to speak up. I politely called out "excuse me sir". He turned around looking shocked that I would even dare to speak like that to him. All the bar tenders looked at me and one said we are busy. I 100% understand being busy and was calmly and patiently waiting but after getting passed over multiple times and seeing people getting served who came up to the bar 10-15 minutes after I did getting served right away I was pissed off. Of course after I said something they really ignored me. When one of the female bartenders who had been in front of finally had nothing else to do but serve me I got a drink. When I asked to speak to a manger it turned out to be the guy who was texting. I explained to him the situation and even apologized if I had offended him for calling out. But that I was still a paying customer and being ignored blatantly like that was not okay. He laughed at me and said its busy this time. Implying that I was being dramatic, not even making eye contact or taking any of it seriously. I have never in my life felt so disrespected and belittled. Do not go near this place and let's hope it closes soon so something much nicer can take its place.

I would go ahead and admit the truth that its pretty cheap. They have the most attractive  happy hour rail drinks ($4) and they also let you mix the drink. You know  guys thats the best way to mix your drink. I love nachos there ($11) which  is so so and so big nd i love it. Its a nice neighborhood restaurant  and becz of the price and fresh food quality we are coming back as long as we live here.

This place was closed when we reached but we had a birthday to celebrate, thank god for KADINE our waitress, she opened the kitchen just for us and believe it or not we had the best food ever and the best hostess too. There was a cheese cake delivered to us with candles to celebrate the birthday and the staff singing happy birthday, man oo man we had a great time

The menu was exciting, and the food was even better! The seafood was great, all the spices and garnishes were unique and excellent. We sensed that the chef was inspired. And even the bill was surprisingly reasonable.
Brunch here is the best and located optimally for a nice city walk after. Try the salmon- truly.
Great service with great food! A place for family or couples with indoor and patio seating. Many great food options on the menu and all are great!

The menu sounded appealing and drew us in.  The food was mediocre, the service was slow for an empty restaurant.  I was done eating when one of the servers was picking his nose.  In the end...not worth it.
Really enjoyed eating here on my visit to D.C. Staff was very friendly, and the food was delicious

The restaurant has been remodeled and updated.  The dining room is beautiful and inviting with lots of space so you don't feel crowded.  Staff are friendly and the food is reasonably priced.  I noticed that they are offering all natural meats and locally resourced produce.  I really like that!
The service is not great and the food is only ok. There are plenty of other places nearby that are much better.
Nothing flavorful at all. The lettuce in the house salad smelled like it was starting to rot. Raviolis and chocolate cake were about as good as frozen food.

I really like Trio, it reminds me of the coffee shops/diners back home in NYC. One of the only places in the city you can go for that diner feel. I love the large outdoor seating area. The service is fine, friendly but sometimes not the most attentive. The best is that they serve breakfast all day- you can't go wrong with eggs and bacon! The restaurant itself feels a little old, but it is the kind of place you go in expecting a decent plate of breakfast food and nothing more. A neighborhood gem if you ask me, and a cheaper alternative to the expensive restaurants that surrounds it!
This is a good place for regular food I was on foot not sure of parking.
Good menu. Food is good.

Food: After a 30 minute wait for my Turkey Cobb salad, which took 5 minutes longer than Chicken Cesar Salad that my boyfriend ordered, my food arrived with hard boiled eggs that were few days old and vinaigrette dressing covering the lettuce which made it looked wilted and it quite possibly could have been.  The dressing also made it extremely hard to spot the sparse pieces of dry turkey.  The Caesar salad wasn't nearly as bad but it all tasted like it came straight out of a bag.  Decor: I don't put much weight into a restaurants decor since it has little to no impact on experience.  That said this place is dark, dirty, and outdated.  Sure, it could use a remodel but they should really focus on food and service.  Service:  After waiting for 20 minutes for two salads we asked our waitress the status of our order to which we were quickly bushed off with an, "It's coming".  A few minutes later she yelled from a few tables away, "a few more minutes on the chicken".  True to her word, a few minutes later the Chicken Caesar Salad came out with no sign or mention of my Turkey Cobb salad.  Finally, 5 minutes later, after 30 minutes of waiting, my less than appetizing salad arrived.  After poking at it for a minute I decided to refuse the food, which I have never done before, due to the time it took and quality of food I received.  The waitress decided informing me that she didn't make the salad is the same as an apology and took the salad back.
Anyone who's a true foodie in the district knows of this place. The sandwiches are nice, real nice, the slices are ridiculous. Second stop every time within a hours drive.
Great little neighborhood spot for a quick breakfast or a burger and beer with a friend. Get an outside spot when the weather permits.
